Introduction¶

The dataset I will investigate (source: Kaggle https://www.kaggle.com/gauravduttakiit/loan-defaulter) contains information about more than 300,000 loan applications. The goal of my analysis is to determine which borrowers' characteristics are mostly associated with delays in paying back the amount lent.

Brief description of the columns used in this analysis:

  • id: loan ID
  • late_payments: 1 if client with payment difficulties
  • gender: gender of the client
  • own_car: Y if client owns a car
  • own_house: Y if client owns a house or flat
  • n_children: number of children the client has
  • income: income of the client in USD
  • loan_amount: amount of the loan in USD
  • education: highest level of education the client achieved
  • family_status: family status of the client (e.g. single, married)
  • age: age at the time of application
  • family_members: number of family members the client has

Random Undersampling¶

As noticed earlier, the main variable of interest "late_payments" is highly imbalanced, as there is a severe skew in its distribution.

In [36]:
plt.figure(figsize=(5,5))
ax = sns.countplot(data=df, x='late_payments')
ax.set_xticklabels(['Timely Payment', 'Late Payment'])
plt.title('Distribution of "late_payments"', fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel('Count', labelpad=15)
plt.xlabel('')
plt.yticks(fontsize=11)
plt.xticks(fontsize=12)
plt.show()

This bias would affect the clarity of my visualizations (as there would be too many values of one category) and the quality of the results of many machine learning algorithms, leading some of them to ignore the minority class entirely. One approach to address this problem is random undersampling, in which observations from the majority class are removed at random until a more balanced distribution is reached.

Therefore I will randomly pick a number of observations from the majority class that is equal to the number of observations in the minority class and remove all the others.

In [37]:
df_late=df.loc[df['late_payments']==1]
n_late=df_late.shape[0] #Get the number of observations with 1 as timely_payments
df_timely=df.loc[df['late_payments']==0].sample(n_late, random_state=42) #Use a fixed random_state for reproducibility
In [38]:
df = pd.concat([df_timely, df_late])

Quick Summary (Data Wrangling)¶

Structure of the dataset:¶

Originally the dataset had 307,511 rows and 122 columns: out of these I immediately selected only the columns that I think are the most relevant for the analysis. After the wrangling phase the resulting dataset has 49,648 rows and 10 columns.

Target variable:¶

The main feature of interest in the dataset is "late_payments", a categorical variable that can assume either 1 if the client had payment difficulties (i.e. he/she made a late payment on at least one of the first installments of the loan), or 0 in case he/she did not.

Other features:¶

I believe all the remaining features might be important in explaining the behavior of my target variable. In particular, I think the most important one is income. Higher income values are likely to be associated with less payment difficulties and vice versa.

The majority of borrowers are between 30 and 45 years old and completed their secondary education. My two assumptions are:

  1. Borrowers with a higher education are less likely to make late payments, because, on average, they have higher incomes;
  2. Older borrowers are less likely to make late payments, because they have higher incomes (unless they are retired) and they probably asked for a lower loan amount, which is easier to pay back.

I will investigate these assumptions in the bivariate exploration.

Quick Summary (Univariate Exploration)¶

Target variable:¶

Originally the distribution of the target variable ("late_payments") was highly imbalanced as there were way more values falling under the category "Timely Payment" compared to "Late Payment". That is why I applied random undersampling and obtained a more balanced distribution. However, no invalid or unusual values were included.

Other features:¶

I found outliers in the variables "income" and "n_children". In the first case I decided to drop the outlier, as it was only a single observation; in the second case I decided to replace the outliers with the most similar value to those that I dropped.

Bivariate Exploration¶

In this section I will investigate the relationships between pairs of variables in the dataset, by focusing in particular on the relationship of my target variable "late_payments" with all the other features.

Let's start by checking the relationship between "late_payments" and "gender", "own_car" and "own_house". Since these are categorical variables I will use clustered bar charts to investigate their relationship.

Earlier I applied random undersampling and obtained a more balanced distribution for the target variable "late_payments". However, as noticed in the univariate exploration, the categories of all the other features are quite imbalanced as well. Let's consider the example below.

In [59]:
plt.figure(figsize=(7,4))
my_order = df['gender'].value_counts().index
sns.countplot(data=df, x='gender', hue='late_payments', order=my_order);
plt.title('Relationship between "gender" and "late_payments"', fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel('Count', labelpad=15)
plt.xlabel('Gender', labelpad=10)
plt.legend(['Timely Payment', 'Late Payment'], fontsize=12, loc = 6, bbox_to_anchor = (1.0, 0.5))
plt.show()

This plot clearly shows that the majority of borrowers are females and that females are more punctual than males. However, due to the different number of observations between the two categories of gender, it is hard to make a comparison between them and identify, within each category, the percentage of borrowers who are punctual in making the payments and those who are not.

To address this issue and be able to make comparison across categories of a single feature, I will represent my target variable "late_payments" as percentage of the total of each category of the feature considered (e.g. in case of "gender", as percentage of the total for male and female).

In [60]:
#Define a function to create bar charts showing the percentages of late payments for each category of a variable
def make_bar_percentage(column, x_size):
    pd.crosstab(df[column], df['late_payments'], normalize='index').plot(figsize=(x_size, 4.5), kind='bar', width=0.8) #Plot
    
    #Modify plot title, labels, legend
    plt.title('Relationship between "'+column+'" and "late_payments"', fontsize=13, y=1.02) #Set title
    plt.ylabel('Percentage by category', labelpad=8, fontsize=12) #Set y axis text, position and size
    plt.yticks((np.arange(0, 1.1, 0.1)), fontsize=9) #Set y ticks size
    plt.gca().yaxis.set_major_formatter(PercentFormatter(1)) #Set percentage format to y axis
    plt.xlabel(column, labelpad=8, fontsize=10) #Set x axis position and size
    plt.xticks(rotation=0, ha='center', fontsize=11) #Set x ticks position and size
    plt.legend(['Timely', 'Late'], title='Payments', title_fontsize= 13, fontsize=12,
               loc=6, bbox_to_anchor=(1.0, 0.5)) #Set legend and movoe it to the right

    #Add labels on top of bars
    x_position=-0.19 #Set initial position
    table = pd.crosstab(df[column], df['late_payments'], normalize='index') #Get crosstab with percentages of total by row
    for i in range(table.shape[0]): #Loop though each row of the table
        for j in range(table.shape[1]): #Loop though each column of the table
            value=table.values[i,j] #Store each value
            plt.text(x_position, value+0.04, '{:.2f}%'.format(value*100), ha='center', va='top') #Print label in percentage
            x_position=x_position+0.41 #Increment position for the adjacent label
        x_position=x_position+0.18 #Increment position for the next category

    plt.show()
In [61]:
make_bar_percentage('gender', 6)

Now I can clearly affirm that males are more likely to make a late payment than females by 10%.

The above chart shows that education has a large effect on "late_payments": as their level of education increases, borrowers are more likely to be punctual in making the payments. Between the lowest and the highest level of education, the percentage difference is about 18%. I believe that this effect is related to the fact that a higher level of education is generally associated with a higher income, and a higher income leads to a smaller probability to make a late payment.

To verify this assumption, I will have to investigate the relationship between "income" and "late_payments" and between "education" and "income".

Quick Summary (Bivariate Exploration)¶

The most important relationships I found between the target variable ("late_payments") and the other features are the following:

  1. Education As their level of education increases, borrowers tend to make less late payments;
  2. Gender Females are more punctual than males;
  3. Number of children As the number of children increases, borrowers tend to make more late payments;
  4. Age Late payments tend to be made more by younger than older people.

I investigated the relationship between education and income and it turns out that, as could be expected, a higher level of education is associated with a higher income. However, surprisingly, I found is that a higher income is not associated with more punctuality of payments.

Exploratory Data Analysis - Conclusions¶

In the bivariate exploration I discovered something surprising:

  • There is a positive relationship between level of education and income, as predictable;
  • There is a negative relationship between the level of education of the borrowers and their probability of making a late payment;
  • However, there is almost no relationship between income and the probability of making a late payment.

Thus it seems that borrowers with a higher level of education tend to pay on time not because they earn more money, but because education is affecting their behavior directly. My hypothesis is that borrowers with higher level of education tend to be more precise and organized, therefore they pay more attention to the due dates of payments.

Let's plot these three variables together in a multivariate chart.

ax = sns.catplot(data=df, x='education', y='income', hue='late_payments', kind='box', height=5, aspect=2.5)

ax._legend.set_bbox_to_anchor([1.05, 0.5])  #Change legend position

    t.set_text(l)
ax.axes[0,0].set_xlabel('') #Remove xlabel

plt.ylim(0,550)
plt.xticks(fontsize=11)

#Add percentage of borrowers per category below each boxplot
x_position=-0.19 #Set initial position
table = pd.crosstab(df['education'], df['late_payments'], normalize='index') #Get crosstab with percentages of total by row
for i in range(table.shape[0]): #Loop though each row of the table
    for j in range(table.shape[1]): #Loop though each column of the table
        value=table.values[i,j]
        plt.text(x_position, -58, '{:.2f}%'.format(value*100), ha='center', va='top') #Print label in percentage
        x_position=x_position+0.41 #Increment position for the adjacent label
    x_position=x_position+0.18 #Increment position for the next category

plt.text(-0.85, -70, '% per category'); #Add text on the bottom left
        
plt.show()

The multivariate chart above shows what I already discovered in the previous phase: as the level of education increases the income increases too, but the distributions of borrowers who paid on time and those who paid late are overlapping in each level of education, showing that income does not have a relevant effect on the punctuality of payments. However, education does: as the level of education increases, the percentage of borrowers making a late payment decreases.

  • Male borrowers are more likely to make late payments than females;
  • Borrowers with a lower level of education are more likely to make late payments than borrowers with a higher level of education.
It is interesting to note that even for low level of educations female borrowers tend to make more payments on time rather than late.

Therefore, according to this analysis the best clients for banks are females with a high level of education; on the contrary, they should take more precautions for men with a low level of education.
